Luis Villegas (born July 28, 1969) is an American guitarist best known for his debut CD Cafe Olé, which mixed new-age music, flamenco, and jazz and garnered a spot on the Grammy ballot for Best New Age Album of the Year in 1999.

Luis played in rock bands all through High School and into college garnering some mild success with the band Slumlord in 1988 and 1989 fronted by Scott Kidd who later went on to become a famous radio DJ known as Uncle Scotty.
Luis quit Slumlord in 1990 when he found he needed a different stimulus to fuel his musical visions.
In 1991, he recorded a demo of original material in a style that was very new to American audiences.
In 1996, Luis recorded and released his first CD independently entitled Café Ole, produced by David Scheffler and Guillermo Guzman.
Domo/EMI released Café Ole with a new cover and some newly recorded songs in 1998.
The album earned a Grammy nomination for Best New Age Album in 1999.
Even larger audiences found Villegas via his next CD, Spanish Kiss (Baja/TSR) in 2000 and the numerous compilation CDs he appeared in during the following two years.
Casa Villegas (Baja/TSR), his third CD, was released in 2003 and marked Luis' debut as a producer as well as performer.
Then, in 2007, the album was updated with several additional songs and a new cover and licensed to the Tenure label, under the guidance of Juan Carlos Quintero.
It was released in August in good time for the 2007 holiday season.
He recorded a duet with classical guitarist Liona Boyd in 2001 which was nominated for a Juno Award (the Canadian Grammy).
In 2003, he performed with Nuevo Flamenco guitarist Jesse Cook, and performed for Carmen Electra and Dave Navarro's much-publicized wedding on MTV in 2004.

In December, 2004 the Luis Villegas Official Fan Club was formed and the members continue to fully support Luis’ music.
On December 21, 2007, Luis was featured in an interview with Val Zavala and performed with several of his band members on the PBS television show "Life and Times."
Heavy Mellow have one self-titled album released in 2013.

Luis Villegas (born July 28, 1969) is an American guitarist best known for his debut CD Cafe Olé, which mixed new-age music, flamenco, and jazz and garnered a spot on the Grammy ballot for Best New Age Album of the Year in 1999.
Currently, he is a member of the group "Heavy Mellow" along with founder Benjamin Woods and percussionist Mike Bennett.
Early years =
Experimental years
Successful years ===
Less than a year later, Luis signed his first recording contract with Domo Records, and affiliate of EMI records.
Even larger audiences found Villegas via his next CD, Spanish Kiss (Baja/TSR) in 2000 and the numerous compilation CDs he appeared in during the following two years.
It stayed on the SmoothJazz.com charts for six weeks after its release on the strength of the single "Whittier Blvd."
Luis was asked by his label, Baja/TSR, to create a Christmas album.
The Christmas album, Guitarras de Navidad found its way to his fans anyway.
It was released in August in good time for the 2007 holiday season.
Luis is currently performing in a band called Heavy Mellow founded by Los Angeles flamenco guitarist Benjamin Woods.
Today, Luis Villegas stays close to the Los Angeles area.
Luis rode his personal style into the Nuevo Flamenco wave and, most recently, he is one of the very few Latino musicians to be popular on smooth jazz stations across the country.
Luis is currently in the studio working on his 5th CD due out this year.

The new CD, under the working title, Eastside, is scheduled for release by the end of the year and is being produced by George Benson's musical director David Garfield and Toto percussionist Chris Trujillo.

He is currently teaching guitar at Santa Monica High School as adjunct faculty for Santa Monica College and flamenco guitar at Orange County High School of the Arts as part of its Instrumental Music Conservatory.
